I'm often creating a blog post that relates somehow to an existing page from another space entirely, and I want to create a link to that page in my post. It feels wrong to just copy and paste the entire/tiny URL, because then you don't get the wiki "nice linking", but at the same time I can't be bothered manually typing in the link to the item (I'm not sure of the syntax for news with the timestamps).

To make this easier, there could be a "wiki link text" field on the Info page for an item, that shows the raw wiki markup you need to copy and paste into your post to make a link. Alternatively, it would be cool if at the bottom of an item, there was a "Link to this page" button, that when clicked shows you the raw wiki markup so that you can copy and paste it.

If the text of a task item includes something in square brackets, it will parse it as a link. If you use a backslash to escape the square brackets, they appear in the text.
Eg
{noformat}[cat]{noformat}
appears as a link to the cat page.

{noformat}\[cat\]{noformat}
appears as
{noformat}\[cat\]{noformat}

Outside the tasklist macro escaping square brackets with backslashes works correctly.  It also works in other macros such as \{panel\}.

If camelcase links are turned on, then file names that specifically have a space and a portion with camelcase in it, ie:

{noformat}
!a ImageFile.jpg! or !this is MyScreenshot.jpg!
{noformat}

The link will not render correctly.

